reviewText: T​his course is not good and there are many problems.  Here are just a few:T​he presenter is not good.  He ums a lot,  so much that it is distracting.I​t is difficult to see how the content could be useful to anyone.T​he presenter does a lot of shilling of his book.T​he quizzes have somewhat random questions.  They ask specific questions about specific celebrity's habits which do not seem to pertain to the subject at hand.  And when bringing up these celebrities in the lectures the presenter is often wrong which is just bizarre.  It appears that he didn't really do much research about the people he is using to illustrate his point.The grading of the quizzes is bizarre.  For a given quiz you can get 11/12 of  multiple choice questions correct and get 2/3  right answers on each of the three multiple choice questions and fail the quiz.

One issue was the use of the term Africa to refer to specific countries; notably when mentioning Carlos working in Phillipines and then by contrast Coco in Africa - please use country-country or continent-continent. Much appreciated course, thanks!

I have enjoyed the course tremendously.   Would like to maintain access for some time to the course material and resource.  Some links to resources and registration are not working. I feel a section on social entrepreneurship in a digital world needs to be added and the content needs to be slightly reviewed and updated following the coronavirus pandemic.

Some of the things you will learn from the course-  how to better Identify causes directly related to your industry, getting a clearer understanding of your objectives , creative ways of leveraging on your products/services and meaningfully engage key stakeholders.
The wording of the questions and the answers sometimes don't completely make sense. They should be reviewed.Other than that, the material in the course is helpful.

I will get back to the course material when I get into a real life situation of social entrepreneurship. I think the steps and the models are very helpful in making more thorough and sustainable decisions.
